# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 29, 1776.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Hanover County Patrick Henry defeated Thomas Nelson Jr. and John Page.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election took place forty-five days after the adoption of the Lee Resolution by the Fifth Virginia Convention declaring the independence of the United Colonies from Great Britain.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of Virginia had been adopted by the convention the same day and went into effect immediately.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The new constitution called for the governor of Virginia to be elected by the votes of the Virginia General Assembly meeting in joint session.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention, as the provisional legislature of the commonwealth, performed this function in the election of 1776.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Prior to 1830, the governor served a term of one year, renewable no more than three times in a seven-year period.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Henry was reelected four times: twice consecutively in 1777 and 1778, and again in 1784 and 1785, to serve a total of five consecutive terms in office.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Fifth Virginia Convention convened in Williamsburg on May 6, 1776, amidst increasingly widespread support for independence among the Patriots who supported the American Revolution.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On May 15, 1776, the convention approved a resolution instructing Virginia's delegates in the Second Continental Congress to support a formal declaration of independence absolving the Thirteen Colonies from their allegiance to the British Empire.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Congress voted to adopt the Lee Resolution on July 2, precipitating passage of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] While Congress debated independence, the Virginia Convention took action to establish the foundations for an independent commonwealth.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A Declaration of Rights was introduced in the convention on May 27 and adopted on June 12; on June 29, the delegates voted unanimously to adopt the proposed Constitution of Virginia.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the Constitution now in place, elections for governor and Attorney General proceeded immediately.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of 1776 called for the governor and other executive officers to be elected by a joint session of the General Assembly, with a majority of votes cast necessary to elect the governor.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The governor was elected for a term of one year and limited to three terms in a seven-year period.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the first General Assembly yet unelected, the Virginia Convention carried out the election of the first governor and Attorney General.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by secret ballot; in all, 106 delegates to the Virginia Convention cast votes for governor.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention elected Henry by a majority of 60 electoral votes to 45 for his nearest competitor, Thomas Nelson.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] George Wythe, James Madison, Bartholomew Dandridge, and William Roscoe Wilson Curl were appointed to inspect the ballots and inform Henry of his election.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1777.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, when the Virginia General Assembly met to conduct the election, the incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was the only candidate nominated.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] By a joint resolution of the Senate and House of Delegates, balloting was dispensed with and Henry was declared re-elected by acclamation.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1778-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1778.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 1, 1779.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Albemarle County Thomas Jefferson defeated the president of the Council of State John Page.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was ineligible for re-election due to term limits established by the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by the Virginia General Assembly in joint session.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] No candidate had a majority after the first count, requiring a second ballot between the two top-finishers.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 2, 1780.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Thomas Jefferson was re-elected.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Senate and the House of Delegates met separately on June 1 to nominate candidates for governor; more than one nomination was made, requiring a vote of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] When the Assembly met in joint session the following day, Jefferson was selected by the majority of members on the first ballot, although the names of the other candidates and the votes tallied were not recorded.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on November 20, 1782.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Benjamin Harrison V was re-elected.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The House of Delegates met on November 19 to make nominations for governor and other offices, which the Senate accepted without amendment; the rule disqualifying votes for candidates other than those nominated was repealed prior to the balloting.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Harrison was selected by a majority of members on the first ballot; the official record of the proceedings does not include the names or tallied votes for any other candidates.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on November 27, 1783.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The House of Delegates met on November 26 to make nominations for governor and other offices, which the Senate accepted without amendment.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On the day of the election, Harrison was selected by a majority of members on the first ballot; the official record of the proceedings does not include the names or tallied votes for any other candidates.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The **2016 United States presidential election in Virginia** was held on November 8, 2016, as part of the 2016 general election in which all 50 states plus the District of Columbia participated.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The Democratic candidate, Hillary Clinton of New York, carried Virginia with a 49.73% plurality in the popular vote against businessman Donald Trump of New York, who carried 44.41%, a victory margin of 5.32%.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Clinton seemed to benefit from having former Virginia governor Tim Kaine on the ticket.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Whereas the national popular vote swung 1.77% Republican from the previous election, Virginia swung 1.44% Democratic.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] However, due to a higher third-party vote, Clinton's percentage was lower than Obama's in both 2008 and 2012 (although her raw vote total slightly improved from Obama in 2012).
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] This was the first time Virginia voted for a losing Democratic candidate since 1924.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The state would later vote for a Democratic nominee who lost the popular vote in 2024 by a larger margin than Clinton's 2016 margin, solidifying the state's status as a blue state.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Conversely, Trump became the first Republican since Calvin Coolidge in 1924 to win the presidency without carrying Virginia.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia had been a traditionally Democratic-leaning state from the party's founding until 1952.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] It then became reliably Republican-leaning from 1952 until 2004, after which point it has voted Democratic in every presidential election.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] As of the 2024 election, Trump in 2016 is the most recent Republican candidate to win Chesapeake, Chesterfield County, James City County, Stafford County, and Virginia Beach.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The 108 delegates (95 pledged delegates and 13 super delegates) from Virginia to the Democratic National Convention were allocated in this way.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Among the pledged delegates, 62 were allocated based on the popular vote in each congressional district.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The 33 at-large delegates were then allocated based on the statewide popular vote.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The 49 delegates from Virginia to the Republican National Convention were allocated proportionally based on the popular vote.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The 2016 Libertarian Party presidential ticket was former New Mexico Governor Gary Johnson for president and former Massachusetts Governor Bill Weld for vice president.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] They earned those nominations at the Libertarian Party 2016 National ConDay weekend.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The Virginia Green Party held its primary from March 20 through April 3.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Party members were able to vote online through an email ballot or through the mail.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] On April 13, it was announced that Jill Stein had won with 76% of the vote.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The state's four delegates were apportioned at the May 28 state meeting.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] In polling, Hillary Clinton won or tied in every pre-election poll but one.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] An average of the last three polls showed Clinton ahead of Trump 48% to 43%, which was accurate compared to the results.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia joined the Union in June 1788 and has participated in all elections from 1789 onwards, except 1864 and 1868 (due to its secession from the US due to the American Civil War).
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Since 1900, Virginia voted Democratic 54.17% of the time and Republican 45.83% of the time.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] From 1968 to 2004, Virginia voted for the Republican Party candidate.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Then, in the 2008 and 2012 elections, the state voted for the Democratic Party.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The same trend continued in the 2016 presidential elections.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Clinton had several advantages in Virginia.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The first was due in part to her landslide win in the Democratic primary against Senator Bernie Sanders.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The second was Virginia has a significant number of African American voters, many of whom backed Clinton in the primary and both of President Barack Obama's wins in the state.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The third was the state's growing share of well-educated suburban voters, especially in the suburbs surrounding Washington, D.C., and Richmond who were moving away from the Republican Party in response to Trump being nominated for president.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The fourth was Clinton's pick of the state's own US Senator, Tim Kaine, as her vice presidential running mate.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] While polls throughout the campaign showed Clinton leading Republican Donald Trump by varying margins in Virginia, it was announced on October 13 that the Trump campaign was pulling its resources out of the state, likely ceding to Clinton what was perceived to be a critical battleground state.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] According to the Trump campaign, the reason for pulling out of Virginia was to compete in more critical battleground states like Pennsylvania, Florida, North Carolina, and Ohio, all of which were states he won.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The following are final 2016 predictions from various organizations for Virginia as of election day.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Despite losing the state, Trump won six of 11 congressional districts, with the remaining five going to Clinton, including one that elected a Republican.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia was the only one of the eleven states that composed the Confederate States of America to vote Democratic in this election.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] This is a reversal from 1976, when it was the only state that had been part of the Confederacy to vote Republican.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia swung leftward from 2012, because of Clinton's gains in Northern Virginia, Albemarle County, Greater Richmond, and Hampton Roads.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] These regions are highly educated, with Northern Virginia and Albemarle County having some of the largest leftward swings and being some of the best-educated areas in the country.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] See the map of the most college-educated counties in the United States.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia was also the only state Hillary Clinton won which was never carried by her husband Bill Clinton in either of his runs for president in 1992 and 1996.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia was one of eleven states (and the District of Columbia) to vote more Democratic than in 2012.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] This was only the third time since Reconstruction that Virginia voted for a different candidate than Florida, after 1976 and 1996, and the first in 140 years in which Virginia voted Democratic while Florida voted Republican.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] This would happen again in 2020 and 2024.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Trump was the first ever Republican to win without Harrisonburg, Manassas, and Manassas Park.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Trump became the first Republican to win the White House without carrying Prince William County and Hopewell since Dwight D.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Eisenhower in 1952, as well as the first to do so without carrying Loudoun County since Herbert Hoover in 1928, and the first to do so without carrying Henrico County, Montgomery County, Staunton, and Winchester since Coolidge in 1924.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Virginia and Colorado have voted for the same presidential candidate in every election since 1996.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] However, this is the last time where Virginia would vote to the left of Colorado.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] Voter demographic data was collected by CNN.
[src:2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia/2016-united-states-presidential-election-in-virginia] The voter survey is based on exit polls.
